{{wiktionary}} {{about|converting military technology|the American veterans' NPO|Swords to Plowshares}} [[File:Schwerter zu Pflugscharen - Bronze - Jewgeni Wutschetitsch - Geschenk der Sowjetunion an die UNO - 1959.jpg|thumb|''Let Us Beat Swords into Plowshares'', a sculpture by [[Evgeniy Vuchetich]] in the [[United Nations Art Collection]]]] '''Swords to ploughshares''' (or '''Swords to plowshares''') is a concept in which military [[weapon]]s or technologies are converted for peaceful civilian applications.
The phrase originates from the [[Book of Isaiah]]:
{{quote|And many people shall go and say, Come ye, and let us go up to the mountain of the {{Sc|L|ORD}}, to the house of the God of Jacob; and He will teach us of His ways, and we will walk in His paths: for out of Zion shall go forth the law, and the word of the {{Sc|L|ORD}} from Jerusalem. And He shall judge among the nations, and shall rebuke many people: and they shall beat their swords into ploughshares, and their spears into pruning hooks: nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they learn war any more.—{{Bibleverse|Isaiah|2:3–4|KJV}}}}
The ''[[plowshare|ploughshare]]'' is often used to symbolize creative tools that benefit humankind, as opposed to destructive tools of war, symbolized by the ''[[sword]]'', a similar sharp metal tool with an arguably opposite use.
In addition to the original Biblical Messianic intent, the expression "beat swords into ploughshares" has been used by disparate social and political groups.
An ongoing example as of 2013 is the dismantling of [[nuclear weapon]]s and the use of their contents as fuel in civilian electric [[power station]]s, the [[Megatons to Megawatts Program]]. [[Nuclear fission]] development, originally accelerated for [[World War II]] weapons needs, has been applied to many civilian purposes since its use at Hiroshima and Nagasaki, including electricity and [[radiopharmaceutical]] production.
==Biblical references== This [[analogy]] is used several times in the [[Old Testament]] or [[Tanakh]], in both directions, such as in the following verses:
{{quote|And he shall judge among the nations, and shall rebuke many people: and they shall beat their swords into plowshares, and their spears into pruninghooks: nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they learn war any more.|{{bibleref|Isaiah|2:4|KJV}}}}
{{quote|Beat your plowshares into swords and your pruninghooks into spears: let the weak say, I am strong.|Christian [[Chapters and verses of the Bible|versification]]: {{bibleref|Joel|3:10|KJV}} Jewish versification: {{bibleref|Joel|4:10|JPR}}}}
{{quote|And he shall judge among many people, and rebuke strong nations afar off; and they shall beat their swords into plowshares, and their spears into pruninghooks: nation shall not lift up a sword against nation, neither shall they learn war any more.|{{bibleref|Micah|4:3|KJV}}}}
An expression of this concept can be seen in a [[bronze]] statue in the [[United Nations]] garden called ''Let Us Beat Swords into Plowshares'', a gift from the [[Soviet Union]] sculpted by [[Evgeniy Vuchetich]], representing the figure of a man hammering a sword into the shape of a plowshare.
==Practical applications== *After World War II, [[military surplus]] [[Armoured fighting vehicle|AFVs]] were sometimes converted into [[bulldozer]]s, agricultural, and logging tractors, as seen in the American television series [[Axe Men]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.warhistoryonline.com/military-vehicle-news/civilianshermans-after-the-war-they-went-to-work.html|title=Civilian Shermans: after the war - they went to work...|first=Simon|last=Templar|date=11 October 2015|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> Two are currently preserved at the [[Swords and Ploughshares Museum]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.inter.nl.net/users/spoelstra/g104/ploughshare.htm|title=Shermans into ploughshares|first=Hanno|last=Spoelstra|website=web.inter.nl.net|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calnan.com/swords/|title=The Swords And Ploughshares Museum|website=www.calnan.com|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> French farmers sometimes used modified versions of the obsolete [[FT-17 tank]], and similar vehicles, based on the [[T-34 tank]], remain in widespread use in the former USSR.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/not_in_website/syndication/monitoring/media_reports/2341811.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Monitoring - Media reports - Ukraine turns tank into tractor|website=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> Robert Crawford, a British agricultural engineer and collector of classic tractors, owns a [[Sherman tank]] that was adapted to plow Lincolnshire's fields in response to the shortage of [[crawler tractor]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.inter.nl.net/users/spoelstra/g104/ploughshare.htm|title=Shermans into ploughshares|first=Hanno|last=Spoelstra|website=web.inter.nl.net|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> * From the 1970s onwards, several [[anti-war]] musicians play guitars made from [[military surplus]] weapons. Jamaican [[reggae]] star [[Pete Tosh]] famously owned a [[Stratocaster]] built around an [[M-16 rifle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diply.com/reggae/article/tosh-m16-guitar|title=More Than Music: Peter Tosh And His M16 Rifle Guitar|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> In the present day the [[Escopetarra]], a guitar converted from the [[AK-47]], is the signature instrument of [[César López]], [[Souriya Sunshine]] and [[Sami Lopakka]] of the Finnish [[death metal]] band [[Sentenced]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/newsletter/en/perspectives/no03/page008.html|title=UNODC Perspectives No. 3 - Escopetarra: Instrument of peace|first=|last=UNODC|website=www.unodc.org|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref> *[[Nitrogen mustard]], developed from the chemical weapon mustard gas developed in World War I,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cwc.gov/assets/pdf/outreach_industry_publications_cwc004.pdf | title =Introduction to Industry Implementation of the Chemical Weapons Convention | author =''[[United States Department of State]]'', ''[[Bureau of Arms Control, Verification and Compliance]]''; ''[[United States Department of Commerce]]'', ''[[Bureau of Industry and Security]]'' | publisher =cwc.gov | date =May 2004}}</ref> became the basis for the world's first chemotherapy drug, [[mustine]], developed through the 1940s.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gilman A |title=The initial clinical trial of nitrogen mustard |journal=Am. J. Surg. |volume=105 |pages=574–8 |date=May 1963 |pmid=13947966 |doi=10.1016/0002-9610(63)90232-0 |issue=5 }}</ref> *Swedish aid organization IM Swedish Development Partner launched Humanium Metal, using metal from illegal handguns to create everyday objects. First product announced was headphones by Yevo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-42599566|title=Illegal guns turned into headphones|last=Kleinman|first=Zoe|date=2018|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>
==In political and popular culture== * Twelve term US Congressman and three time presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]] wrote a book entitled ''Swords into Plowshares: A Life in Wartime and a Future of Peace and Prosperity'', in which he discusses growing up during World War II and living his life through war after war.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Swords-into-Plowshares-Ron-Paul/dp/0996426507|title=Swords into Plowshares|first=Ron|last=Paul|date=17 July 2015|publisher=Ron Paul Institute for Peace and Prosperity|accessdate=11 June 2017|via=Amazon}}</ref> * In his [[Eisenhower's farewell address|farewell address]], U.S. President [[Dwight Eisenhower]], when speaking about the [[military-industrial complex]] stated: {{quote|Until the latest of our world conflicts, the United States had no armaments industry. American makers of plowshares could, with time and as required, make swords as well. But now we can no longer risk emergency improvisation of national defense; we have been compelled to create a permanent armaments industry of vast proportions. Added to this, three and a half million men and women are directly engaged in the defense establishment. We annually spend on military security more than the net income of all United States corporations.}} * For his [[First inauguration of Richard Nixon|first]] and [[Second inauguration of Richard Nixon|second]] inaugurations, U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]] took the oath of office with his hand on two family Bibles, opened to Isaiah 2:2-4.<ref name="UPI 1969">{{cite news |author=United Press International (UPI) |title=Protestors' shouts mar inaugural ceremonies | date=20 January 1973 | url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1973/01/20/Protestors-shouts-mar-inaugural-ceremonies/9270282371459/ | access-date=18 October 2017}}</ref><ref>http://time.com/4639596/inauguration-day-presidents-bible-passages/</ref><ref name="Ross 2013">{{cite web | last=Ross | first=Scott | title=Obama's Inaugural Bibles: Lincoln, MLK | website=NBC 6 South Florida | date=21 January 2013 | url=http://www.nbcmiami.com/news/national-international/Inuaration-Day-Bibles-and-Passages-186343462.html | access-date=18 October 2017}}</ref> * In their speeches at the signing of the 1979 [[Egypt–Israel Peace Treaty]], [[Jimmy Carter]], [[Anwar Sadat]], and [[Menachem Begin]] all referenced the saying in calling for peace.<ref>{{cite book|title=Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States, Jimmy Carter| year=1979 |publisher= Office of the Federal Register|pages=518–520|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j_5-9zWaBI0C&pg=PA518#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> * In [[Ronald Reagan]]'s Address to the 42nd Session of the [[United Nations General Assembly]] in New York, New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/speeches/1987/092187b.htm |title=Ronald Reagan Presidential Library Archives |publisher=UTexas.edu |date=1987-09-21 |accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> {{quote|Cannot swords be turned to plowshares? Can we and all nations not live in peace? In our obsession with antagonisms of the moment, we often forget how much unites all the members of humanity. Perhaps we need some outside, universal threat to make us recognize this common bond. I occasionally think how quickly our differences world-wide would vanish if we were facing an alien threat from outside this world. And yet, I ask you, is not an alien force already among us? What could be more alien than war and the threat of war?}} *The popular [[anti-war movement|anti-war]] song "The Vine and Fig Tree" repeats the verse<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.fredsakademiet.dk/abase/sange/greenham/song9.htm |title=Greenham Common Women's Peace Camp Songbook |publisher=Fredsakademiet.dk |accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref> {{quote|<poem>And everyone neath their vine and fig tree shall live in peace and unafraid, Everyone neath their vine and fig tree shall live in peace and unafraid. And into ploughshares beat their swords Nations shall learn war no more. And into ploughshares beat their swords Nations shall learn war no more.</poem>}} *The song "[[The End of the Innocence (song)|The End of the Innocence]]" by [[Don Henley]] (1989) uses the Joel inverted version of the phrase: {{quote|<poem>O' beautiful, for spacious skies But now those skies are threatening They're beating plowshares into swords For this tired old man that we elected king</poem>}} * "[[Heal the World]]" by [[Michael Jackson]] (1991): {{quote|<poem>Create a world with no fear Together we'll cry happy tears See the nations turn Their swords into plowshares</poem>}} * Finale of the musical ''[[Les Misérables (musical)|Les Misérables]]'': {{quote|<poem>They will live again in freedom In the garden of the Lord. They will walk behind the ploughshare, They will put away the sword. The chain will be broken And all men will have their reward.</poem>}}
* A poem by Israeli poet [[Yehuda Amichai]]: {{quote|<poem>Don’t stop after beating the swords into plowshares, don’t stop! Go on beating and make musical instruments out of them. Whoever wants to make war again will have to turn them into plowshares first.</poem>}}
